      Squid Game Coin
   =20
 =20
Here are three sentences that I found on the internet:SQUID implements an i=
nnovative anti-dump mechanism where buying in the market will release selli=
ng credits at a rate of 2:1.The maximum amount of SQUID that can be sold is=
 half of the total buying value in the pool. When the credit in the pool is=
 depleted, you can=E2=80=99t sell any more.That=C2=A0is=C2=A0an innovative =
anti-dump mechanism! Whenever stocks or cryptocurrencies go up, someone wil=
l half-joke that the explanation is =E2=80=9Cmore buyers than sellers.=E2=
=80=9D If you just=C2=A0build into the design of your cryptocurrency=C2=A0t=
hat there always have to be twice as many buyers as sellers, it will always=
 go up.Obviously that sentence makes no sense, and SQUID =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 Squid Game Token =E2=80=94=C2=A0did not always go up during its short life=
. Well, actually it did =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt surged more than 230,000=
% in the past week to $2,861.80,=E2=80=9D  says Bloomberg News =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0until its anonymous developers apparently stole all the=C2=A0money; then=
 it went down. The whole thing is so stupid and overdetermined that I canno=
t bear to write about it; if you lost money on SQUID you should just come t=
o my house and give me your wallet because you should not be allowed to use=
 money anymore. =E2=80=9CNew Squid Game Cryptocurrency Launches as Obvious =
Scam,=E2=80=9D reported Matt Novak at Gizmodo last week, before it crashed,=
 listing red flags like =E2=80=9CNetflix=E2=80=99s Squid Game is the most p=
opular streaming show in the world right now, so it makes sense that scamme=
rs would use the name without permission,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe website=
 for the Squid Game crypto even includes a fake endorsement from billionair=
e Elon Musk,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe single largest red flag is the fact =
that people can put money in, but can=E2=80=99t take it out.=E2=80=9D Accor=
ding to the now-disappeared white paper there was purportedly a mechanism t=
o take money out by (1) spending a lot of SQUID coins to play a=C2=A0game, =
(2) winning the game, (3) collecting some other related cryptocurrency and =
then (4) being allowed to sell your SQUID freely if you had that currency. =
But, come on, instead they just stole all the money.I do, however, want to =
talk about that anti-dumping mechanism, which I love. It is a basic fact ab=
out financial markets that if lots of people want to buy an asset and nobod=
y wants to sell it, the price will go up. (Strictly, if=C2=A0nobody=C2=A0wa=
nts to sell it, there will be no trades and no price, but if=C2=A0very few =
people very reluctantly=C2=A0sell it then there will be some trades and the=
 price will go up.) In general this is sort of an epiphenomenon of some mor=
e fundamental reason that=C2=A0people want to buy it.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMore bu=
yers than sellers=E2=80=9D is a=C2=A0joke, a=C2=A0non-explanation; if someo=
ne asks you why=C2=A0Tesla stock=C2=A0went up and you say =E2=80=9Cmore buy=
ers than sellers=E2=80=9D you are just being annoying and obtuse.[5]But in =
modern crypto and meme-stock markets this basic fact has been distilled int=
o a fundamental belief, free of any underlying reason. =E2=80=9CIf we all b=
uy this thing and don=E2=80=99t sell it, the price will go up, and then we=
=E2=80=99ll be rich=E2=80=9D is a belief that is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of log=
ical? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and that can be applied to anything. =E2=80=9CIf we al=
l buy GameStop Corp. stock,=E2=80=9D etc.; there the belief went by the nam=
e =E2=80=9Cdiamond hands.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIf we all buy Bitcoin,=E2=80=9D=
 etc.; there it goes by the name =E2=80=9CHODL.=E2=80=9D There is a new gen=
eration of crypto stuff like Olympus DAO, where it goes by the name =E2=80=
=9C(3,3),=E2=80=9D a vague wave in the direction of game theory: =E2=80=9C(=
3,3) is the idea that, if everyone cooperated in Olympus, it would generate=
 the greatest gain for everyone (from a game theory standpoint).=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9CCooperate=E2=80=9D in that sentence just means buying=C2=A0a lot a=
nd never selling.=C2=A0This belief has a basic mechanical=C2=A0problem, whi=
ch is that if you all buy the thing and don=E2=80=99t sell it and become ri=
ch, you can=E2=80=99t actually=C2=A0use=C2=A0your riches without selling th=
e thing. Sometimes this takes the shape of a pump and dump: People buy the =
thing, it goes up, they get rich on paper, they try to cash out, it crashes=
, some of them are left holding the bag. Sometimes, though, it takes the sh=
ape of, like, mass adoption and stable wealth? If you bought a lot of Bitco=
ins at $2 you are very rich now and you can probably cash out enough wealth=
 to buy a yacht without really affecting the price of Bitcoin. Bitcoin just=
 kind of made it.The weirdest thing=C2=A0that  I think about is that=C2=A0G=
ameStop=C2=A0might also have kind of made it? If you got rich on GameStop y=
ou can sell your GameStop stock and be rich and the price might be unaffect=
ed either by your selling or by the underlying cash flows of GameStop the c=
ompany. That is much weirder than Bitcoin because GameStop is a company. Bu=
t the point is that when I say that this belief=C2=A0can be applied to anyt=
hing, I also=C2=A0mean that it might=C2=A0work for anything. Like, why not,=
 mass societal adoption of GameStop as a store of value, stranger things ha=
ve happened though I cannot actually think of one.SQUID did not make it, ob=
viously. But its marketing is instructive. The marketing was =E2=80=9Cpeopl=
e can buy it but they can=E2=80=99t sell it.=E2=80=9D Skeptics, correctly, =
interpreted this as a mark of a scam. But it was marketed as a=C2=A0good th=
ing, an innovative way to design a coin that would always go up because peo=
ple would buy and not sell it. There is a lot of demand for that!
