<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oops</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do not want to say that losing a lot=
 of money on a trade is=C2=A0<em>as good=C2=A0</em>as making a lot of money=
 on a trade. It is not. For one thing, if you make=C2=A0a lot of money on a=
 trade, then you have money, which can be used to buy goods and services. F=
or another thing, if you make a lot of money on a trade, then you were at l=
east in some rough sense=C2=A0<em>correct=C2=A0</em>about the trade, and be=
ing correct often about big questions is a valuable skill in finance and li=
fe.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you lose a lot of money on a t=
rade, neither of those things are true. And yet there is a certain prestige=
 to it? Being correct is not the whole ballgame. Being=C2=A0<em>important=
=C2=A0</em>is important. =E2=80=9CImportant people like to deal with import=
ant people,=E2=80=9D the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMDYvYmUtY2FyZWZ1bC13ZWFyaW5nLWplYW5zLWF0LWdvbGRtYW4_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMTEwMzIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBf1253bac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> Goldman Sachs commandment</a> goes; =E2=80=9Car=
e you one?=E2=80=9D The most famous JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. trader of the =
last decade, the one JPMorgan trader whom many people know by name or at le=
ast by nickname, is Bruno Iksil, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9xdWlja3Rh=
a2UvdGhlLWxvbmRvbi13aGFsZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAzMjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTExMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7a916291" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the London Wh=
ale</a>, who is famous for losing $6.2 billion of the bank=E2=80=99s money.=
 Did that work out great for him? No, not really, not at all. But I suspect=
 a lot of people in finance would buy him a drink if they ran into him. He =
is a celebrity in a way that thousands of traders who have never lost $6 bi=
llion are not.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, as I have <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjYvZXh4b24taGF=
zLWEtdG91Z2gtZ3JlZW4tYWN0aXZpc3Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMzIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTAzJnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB87859cb7" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> written=
 before</a>, it is a rule of thumb in high finance that losing a lot of mon=
ey on a trade can be good for your career: It shows that someone has truste=
d you to take risk, and that you took risk, and while it didn=E2=80=99t wor=
k out you probably learned from your mistakes. That may not=C2=A0work at th=
e celebrity level, but if you were just=C2=A0<em>around=C2=A0</em>the Londo=
n Whale losses you probably have some good war stories that any interviewer=
 will appreciate.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway I predict a bright=
 future for the house traders who lost $300 million trading houses for Zill=
ow and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25568325.26=
5653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMDIvem=
lsbG93LXNodXRzLWRvd24taG9tZS1mbGlwcGluZy1idXNpbmVzcy1hZnRlci1yYWNraW5nLXVwL=
Wxvc3Nlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAzMjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTExMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf13e03bb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> got not only themselves but=C2=
=A0<em>25% of the company=C2=A0</em>fired</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Zillow Group Inc. is pulling the plug on its tech-powered h=
ome-flipping operation, after an ambitious effort to transform the company =
collapsed when its vaunted pricing algorithms proved unequal to the task.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company plans to take writedowns of as m=
uch as $569 million and reduce its workforce by 25% as it winds down the bu=
siness in coming months, according to a statement Tuesday. Zillow shares pl=
unged as much as 11% to $76.22 in late trading.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The decision to abandon home flipping comes as the company=E2=80=99s t=
hird-quarter results showed it lost more than $380 million in the operation=
, called Zillow Offers. The business hit a major snag in recent months as Z=
illow tweaked its algorithms to make more aggressive offers, causing it to =
overpay for houses just as the heated U.S. market began to cool slightly.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With the company=E2=80=99s losses mo=
unting, Chief Executive Officer Rich Barton said it had become too risky to=
 scale the business in a U.S. housing market that has been running hot for =
well over a year during the pandemic.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=
=80=9CFundamentally, we have been unable to predict future pricing of homes=
 to a level of accuracy that makes this a safe business to be in,=E2=80=9D =
Barton said on an earnings call.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I say =E2=80=9Ctraders=E2=80=9D because that is sort of the conventional=
 way to describe people who lose hundreds of millions of dollars of their e=
mployers=E2=80=99 capital doing trades, but I suppose the more correct desc=
ription is, like, =E2=80=9Calgorithm designers.=E2=80=9D Zillow did not hir=
e a team of house traders to make gut-instinct-based calls on housing valua=
tion; it hired a team of programmers to build a house-buying algorithm. And=
 they did, and it was cool, but it lost $300 million last quarter and is no=
w getting shut down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also I should say that=
 Zillow=E2=80=99s traders (or rather its algorithm) are not the sorts of tr=
aders who are supposed to lose hundreds of millions of dollars. They were=
=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>entrusted to take big risks, to swing for the fence=
s; they did not aim for a massive profit, miss, and land on a massive loss =
instead. They were market makers; they were supposed to buy at the bid, sel=
l at the offer, collect a spread for providing liquidity and make a steady =
profit. Here=E2=80=99s how Barton put it on the <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL3N0b3JpZXMvUjFZVEZWR0pDRDFHP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDMyMV9NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTE=
wMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb16fa484" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> earnings call</a> yesterday[1]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">When we decided to take a big swing on Zillow offers 3.5 years ago, o=
ur aim was to become a market maker not a market risk taker. And this was u=
nderpinned by the need to forecast the price of homes accurately three to s=
ix months in the future.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We used historical=
 data and countless simulations to test this belief. We set unit economics =
targets that required us to stay within plus or minus 200 basis points in b=
reakeven, holding ourselves accountable to these levels publicly with you a=
ll.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The central problem is tha=
t those first two sentences sort of contradict each other. A market maker i=
s someone who buys and sells an asset in order to profit from the spread, n=
ot someone who accurately forecasts the price of an asset six months from n=
ow. End users want to buy or sell stocks or bonds or houses, they want to d=
o it quickly at a predictable price, so they go to a market maker who will =
provide that service. The market maker buys from sellers and sells from buy=
ers and does its best to match them up; ideally it buys an asset from a sel=
ler and resells it to a buyer within a fairly short time. It collects a =E2=
=80=9Cspread=E2=80=9D from the buyer and seller: It buys from the buyer at =
a bit less than the fair market price, and sells to the seller at a bit mor=
e than the fair market price, because it is providing them a valuable servi=
ce, the service of =E2=80=9Cimmediacy=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cliquidity,=E2=80=
=9D the service of always being available to buy or sell.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In pure theory the market maker makes all of its money=
 from the spread; it is so perfectly hedged, or turns over its inventory so=
 frequently, that it doesn=E2=80=99t care if the prices of stocks or bonds =
or houses go=C2=A0up or down. In practice this is impossible and all market=
 makers have some amount of inventory risk; at any moment they are long or =
short some amount of assets, and if prices move they will make or lose mone=
y. Still, to the extent=C2=A0you are a pure market maker, you try to minimi=
ze that.[2]=C2=A0In the stock market, high-frequency electronic market make=
rs really do turn over their inventory so often that they can reliably coll=
ect spreads without worrying too much about price movements. Famously Virtu=
 Financial Inc., one of those market makers,=C2=A0can <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDItMjAvaGlnaC1mcmVxdWVuY3ktdHJhZGVyLX=
ZpcnR1LWV4dGVuZHMtbmVhcmx5LXVuYmxlbWlzaGVkLXN0cmVhaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAzMjFfT=
U9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVy=
bT0yMTExMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb702a8=
2b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> go years without a down day</a>: It makes money (from spreads=
) every single day, whether the stock market=C2=A0goes up or=C2=A0down. It =
is trading stocks all day, but in some important sense it is not betting on=
 stock prices.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in the house busin=
ess you can=E2=80=99t generally buy a house in the morning and sell it in t=
he afternoon. You sign a contract to buy a house in the morning, then you d=
o an inspection and title search and stuff, then a few weeks later you clos=
e on the house and deliver the money, then you spruce up the house a bit, t=
hen you wait for a buyer to come in =E2=80=94=C2=A0which takes, not seconds=
 as it does in the stock market, but days or weeks or months =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then you show the house to the buyer, then you sign a contract to sell i=
t, then they=C2=A0do an inspection and title search and stuff, then you wai=
t around for=C2=A0them=C2=A0to get a mortgage, then a few months later you =
close on the sale.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And meanwhile the price =
of houses has gone up or down, and the effect of that dwarfs the effect of =
your spread. This past quarter Zillow <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0F=
yY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTYxNzY0MC8wMDAxNjE3NjQwMjEwMDAwODcvei0yMDIxMDkzMC=
5odG0jaWFmODVjNzgxMzU3OTQ5ZWNhOGNiOTg0NjhiMDExZTg4XzM0/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB79aa4ad3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">wrote down its inventory of houses</a> by $304 milli=
on, to $3.8 billion,=C2=A0a loss of something like 750 basis points, way wo=
rse than the 200 basis point spread it was targeting.[3] But the quarter be=
fore that =E2=80=94=C2=A0April through June of 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0it had a=
 gain of 576 basis points. =E2=80=9CClearly some portion of the holding cos=
ts and a smaller portion of the renovation costs likely benefited from the =
strong housing market,=E2=80=9D Barton <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/25568325.265653/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL3N0b3JpZXMvUVhFMUdER0pDRDFIP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDMyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0b=
V9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTEwMyZ1dG1f=
Y2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb32b2913" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">said =
at the time</a>: House prices went up, so Zillow, which owned a bunch of ho=
uses, made more money than it planned to. As Barton said on yesterday=E2=80=
=99s call, both results are a problem:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">We've been unable to accurately forecast future home prices at diff=
erent times in both directions by much more than we modeled as possible. Wi=
