ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">last quarter=E2=80=99s 10-Q</a>.<=
/em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[5] I should say that there are tw=
o objections to =E2=80=9Cmore buyers than sellers.=E2=80=9D One is that it =
is a non-explanation: When people ask why the market went up, they want you=
 to give them a *reason*, and =E2=80=9Cmore buyers than sellers=E2=80=9D is=
 just a tautological rephrasing of =E2=80=9Cthe market went up.=E2=80=9D Th=
e other objection, though, is that it isn=E2=80=99t true: Every time a shar=
e of stock or a cryptocurrency trades, there is one buyer and one seller, s=
o there are never =E2=80=9Cmore buyers than sellers.=E2=80=9D (Or there mig=
ht be =E2=80=94=C2=A0100 people might each buy one share from one person wh=
o sells 100 shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in a trivial and irrelevant way.) In =
general you sort of know what =E2=80=9Cmore buyers than sellers=E2=80=9D me=
ans, it means that there is more buying demand, more bids, more enthusiasm =
from buyers than sellers, etc. But SQUID=E2=80=99s anti-dumping mechanism *=
literally* required more buys than sells. This is impossible, of course, wh=
ich I suppose is why people couldn=E2=80=99t sell.</em></p>
